        <div class="ad-zone-label">Advertisement</div>
        <ins class="adsbygoogle" style="display:block"
          data-ad-client="ca-pub-5193834725888549"
          data-ad-slot="4212978293"
          data-ad-format="auto"
          data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
        <script>(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});</script>
      </div>
      <% } %>

      <div class="calc-card-form">
        <h2>Enter Your Business Information</h2>
        <form method="POST" action="/self-employment-tax-calculator">
          <div class="form-grid">
            <div class="form-field full">
              <label for="grossIncome">Gross Annual 1099 Business Income</label>
              <div class="input-wrap"><span class="input-prefix">$</span>
                <input type="number" id="grossIncome" name="grossIncome" min="0" step="any" value="<%= form.grossIncome || '' %>" placeholder="95000" required>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="form-field full">
              <label for="businessExpenses">Annual Business Deductions / Operational Expenses</label>
              <div class="input-wrap"><span class="input-prefix">$</span>
                <input type="number" id="businessExpenses" name="businessExpenses" min="0" step="any" value="<%= form.businessExpenses || '' %>" placeholder="15000">
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="form-actions">
            <button type="submit" class="btn-calc">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M14 2H6a2 2 0 00-2 2v16a2 2 0 002 2h12a2 2 0 002-2V8z"/><polyline points="14 2 14 8 20 8"/></svg>
              Calculate Self-Employment Tax
            </button>
          </div>
        </form>
      </div>

      <div class="hiw-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">How It Works</div>
        <h2>How 1099 Self-Employment Tax Is Assessed</h2>
        <p>Unlike standard employees, independent operators fulfill both the employee and employer halves of the FICA framework structure lines.</p>
        <div class="hiw-steps">
          <div class="hiw-step">
            <div class="hiw-step-num">1</div>
            <div class="hiw-step-body">
              <h3>Find Your True Net Profit</h3>
              <p>Subtract your raw business workspace deductions and hardware overhead expenses from your gross annual 1099 invoice income base line.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="hiw-step">
            <div class="hiw-step-num">2</div>
            <div class="hiw-step-body">
              <h3>Apply the 92.35% Assessment Boundary</h3>
              <p>The IRS assesses SE liabilities against exactly 92.35% of your net operational profit line, factoring in the employer tax matching offset rule automatically.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="hiw-step">
            <div class="hiw-step-num">3</div>
            <div class="hiw-step-body">
              <h3>Evaluate FICA Structural Parameters</h3>
              <p>Social Security tax evaluates at 12.4% up to the baseline index limit ($176,100 for 2025). Medicare tax evaluates at 2.9% across your total net balance margin lines.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="hiw-step">
            <div class="hiw-step-num">4</div>
            <div class="hiw-step-body">
              <h3>Claim Your Above-the-Line Half Offset</h3>
              <p>When executing your Form 1040, exactly 50% of your total computed SE liability can be written off as an adjustment to reduce federal income tax lines.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="formula-box">
          <div class="formula-box-label">Formula Reference</div>
          <code><span class="comment">// SE Parameter Assessment Math</span>
<span class="highlight">Net Business Profit</span> = Gross 1099 Income - Expenses
<span class="highlight">Assessable Income</span>   = Net Business Profit x 92.35%

<span class="comment">// Rate Metrics</span>
Social Security Tax = Assessable Income x 12.4% (Up to Limit threshold boundary)
Medicare Tax        = Assessable Income x 2.9%</code>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">FAQ</div>
        <h2>Contractor Liability Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Who is required to pay self-employment tax liabilities?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Anyone generating net self-employment earnings of $400 or more during a designated filing year must fulfill self-employment tax liabilities using Schedule SE.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Does this tool compute my state income tax obligations?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No, this engine estimates federal self-employment FICA obligations only. State income calculations utilize completely separate bracket policies depending on region.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="page-disclaimer">
        <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/><line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/></svg>
        <p><strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This application calculates estimated baseline framework metrics for forward planning purposes. It is not professional advice. Verify parameters with a professional before filing quarterly schedules.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </main>

